kind of healthcare insurance typically works. Usually we work with brokers who work at brokerages.

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.959
So it's kind of a B2B2C space. So it's not like a car insurance company where you sell

00:06:52.959 --> 00:06:58.880
directly to the consumer. So there is kind of a sense of how can we prioritize the service for,

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:05.839
you know, our swath of brokerages we work with. So probably similar in kind of a direct to consumer

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:10.160
space. You know, who do I send my really high touch marketing to? Who do I spend a lot of time

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:17.359
doing outreach to? Yeah. Okay. Thank you. That's super helpful. Yeah. I see there was an anonymous

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:24.079
question that came in on Slido about talking about open source. So when you think about that,

00:07:24.079 --> 00:07:34.640
how does Stack Overflow fit into that? So I am maybe a bad example of a Stack Overflow

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:39.200
contributor. So I am very much a consumer of Stack Overflow. I'm a little intimidated to

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:47.519
my own questions, but I think Stack Overflow is hugely kind of, obviously it's impactful. I'm sure

00:07:47.519 --> 00:07:54.239
every single person on this call has used Stack Overflow quite a bit. I have never come across

00:07:54.239 --> 00:07:59.279
somebody who was a big Stack Overflow contributor from an interviewing perspective, but that would

00:07:59.279 --> 00:08:06.880
be amazing if I did. I think actually one of my coworkers' father is one of the great contributors

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:14.160
to Stack Overflow and our forums. So I know I was just super excited to talk to him. And to me,

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:18.880
that's just the highest honor in terms of contribution to the open source community,

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:23.119
in my opinion, is really contributing to Stack Overflow questions, reproducible examples,

00:08:23.119 --> 00:08:30.079
but then the answers as well. Awesome. I see Tatiana in the chat. You had a great question

00:08:30.079 --> 00:08:37.280
there and I'd love to have you ask that live too. Sure. I was about to type in. Sorry.

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:43.840
Yeah, sure. It's more of a philosophical question to get us started. I imagine you have one team,

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:49.599
obviously, but since you do present yourself as a director of analytics and data science,

00:08:49.599 --> 00:08:55.359
I would be curious to hear about how do you think about the differences between the two? And I see

00:08:55.359 --> 00:09:00.320
that initially you were a manager of advanced analytics and then data science was kind of like

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:06.400
joined afterwards. Does it mean that you started undertaking more forecasting and predictive

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:11.840
analysis and how do you think about the two? And if you have the split in responsibilities in your

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:17.039
team members who are responsible, one for advanced analytics and one for data science, how you

00:09:17.039 --> 00:09:23.919
can comment on that? Yeah, that's a great question. So I think the delineation of data science and

00:09:23.919 --> 00:09:29.039
analytics looks probably a little different at every business. So I'll just caveat it with my

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:34.640
answer is not the right one, in my opinion. It's just kind of how I think about it. So data science

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:40.640
and analytics are two different but really related teams. So they work together quite collaboratively.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:48.159
So we have shared lab meetings, shared team meetings for now. I think as teams grow in size,

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:52.799
obviously, that can be harder to keep that cohesion together. We also really work extremely

00:09:52.799 --> 00:09:58.159
closely with data management now. So we have, you know, same stand-ups. I could see in the future

00:09:58.159 --> 00:10:03.039
there'd be kind of from a just like functional perspective delineations of that from a meeting

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:08.239
perspective. But I think it's really important to keep that bridge together. In terms of how I think

00:10:08.239 --> 00:10:12.000
of the differences between analytics and data science. So first thing that comes to mind is from

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.119
a tool stack perspective. Traditionally, I think the analysts are much heavier on the SQL skills,

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:23.679
much heavier on BI skills. So a traditional analyst that I'm typically interviewing or hiring

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:30.000
is much more likely to have experience with like Tableau or Looker versus a Shiny. Shiny,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:35.039
for example, typically when I start to see example with something like Shiny, I also see really strong

00:10:35.039 --> 00:10:39.280
programming in R or Python. And then often it tends to kind of correlate with the deeper

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:45.359
statistics background. So that's from a tooling perspective, some delineation. So our data science

00:10:45.359 --> 00:10:52.320
team definitely more focused on Python and R versus traditional BI platforms. SQL really common

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:58.320
amongst both of the teams, but it's pretty strong among our analysts from a skillset perspective. In

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:04.159
terms of functional problems, how I like to describe it is I view the analyst as kind of the business

00:11:04.159 --> 00:11:09.359
data consultants. So they're often tackling kind of vague questions. So it might be a trend that's

00:11:09.359 --> 00:11:14.159
being observed in the business and their task is to kind of dig in from a data perspective and find

00:11:14.719 --> 00:11:22.239
indicators that might be indicative of why that trend is occurring. And also maybe qualitatively,

00:11:22.239 --> 00:11:27.359
or I should say kind of from a trend perspective, indicative of what might happen in the future.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:31.599
But they might actually not get to the level of building the predictive model to make that happen.

00:11:31.599 --> 00:11:36.000
It's more kind of extrapolation from visual trends often, and some basic kind of descriptive

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.799
statistics. And then a heavy amount of like data storytelling, which I know can be a general term,

00:11:40.799 --> 00:11:46.719
but I do think it's a core aspect of what they do. And then also just bread and butter reporting.

00:11:46.719 --> 00:11:53.119
So how are we doing as a business on our key metrics, right? So wins, our deal sizes, et cetera,

00:11:53.119 --> 00:12:00.559
just the staple daily refreshing tracking of that. Data scientists, often they will be working on a

00:12:00.559 --> 00:12:05.440
very specific problem that was uncovered from the analyst. So usually a predictive model.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:11.919
There are definitely some automation projects that are using tools like Python, but in my mind,

00:12:11.919 --> 00:12:17.039
kind of more traditional automation work. So if you could imagine something like extracting

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:21.760
information from PDFs, right? Requires kind of a data science skillset, might be a probabilistic

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:27.840
model underneath that, but could also just be solved with some kind of classic tools.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:32.320
And then from an end user's perspective, you are automating their workflow, right?

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:39.280
Even though it is in essence, just programming. So data science, more specific focus problems,

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:44.479
less stakeholder facing time, more development time, predictive modeling problems and automation

00:12:44.479 --> 00:12:49.679
analyst really partners to the business and those data consultants. So hopefully that helped. That's

00:12:49.679 --> 00:12:54.640
just how I have the view I have shaped, but could be much different other places.

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:56.880
That's fantastic. Thank you. Yeah.

00:12:57.840 --> 00:13:02.479
Thanks Katie. Mark, I see you had a great question in the chat too, if you want to jump in.

00:13:05.599 --> 00:13:12.960
Yeah, sure. Sorry, I was on mute. Katie, you mentioned you have your data scientists on the

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:19.039
team use both Python and R. I guess like how do you manage that mix of languages within the team?

00:13:20.320 --> 00:13:26.239
That's a good question. So admittedly, I am the person who is the R user and R2

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:32.799
kind of core data scientist or Python users. So I'd say the vast majority of the development code

00:13:32.799 --> 00:13:39.599
and production code is in Python. In terms of how we manage it though, I think it seems simpler in

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:45.200
practice than I pictured it to be. So both of the data scientists are really strong in Python and

00:13:45.200 --> 00:13:52.719
have dabbled in R at least, if not used it in a master's program, et cetera. So they can read R

00:13:52.719 --> 00:13:57.440
and I can read Python and vice versa. But if either one of us were going to build something,

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:03.039
it would be much quicker to do it in our preferred language. I am kind of a proponent

00:14:03.039 --> 00:14:07.520
of the right tool for the job. So most of these things we have not tackled quite yet,

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:12.559
but on our roadmap, there are certainly problems that I foresee R being the better tool because

00:14:12.559 --> 00:14:17.679
there's a more robust set of statistical packages out there for kind of niche problems.

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:24.159
So I'm a big proponent of right tool for the job, right tool for you, but I'd say

00:14:25.840 --> 00:14:30.640
anyone who's fairly strong in one typically doesn't have problems reading the other or

00:14:30.640 --> 00:14:36.320
interpreting the other. So I will often do code reviews or coaching sessions on Python code,

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:40.799
even though I'm not the expert in Python, it's pretty quick for us to get on the same page of

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:45.599
what I'm trying to convey or what they're trying to convey. And conceptually, most of our like

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:50.159
working sessions are going to be more about the model we're choosing, the performance metrics,

00:14:50.159 --> 00:14:55.200
et cetera, features that we want to include, and a little bit less about the specifics of code.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:59.919
So if you're hiring kind of really new novice talent, yes, absolutely. I do think it's critical

00:14:59.919 --> 00:15:03.919
that you're really strong in the language you want to train them on or somebody who's senior

00:15:03.919 --> 00:15:08.239
on your team is, that would be a problem. But since we kind of started out with some

00:15:08.239 --> 00:15:13.119
more senior folks, they are pretty savvy in one or the other, but they do have a preference.

00:15:14.080 --> 00:15:16.479
Cool. Thank you. Yeah.

00:15:17.039 --> 00:15:22.159
Thanks, Katie. Kind of following up on that, I see Robert had asked the question as well,

00:15:22.159 --> 00:15:27.599
that was, how do you think through which tool is the right one for the project or requirement?

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:32.960
And I think that might go even into like when you talked about the data analyst side of the

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:38.320
house using Looker, for example, too. That's a good question. We actually have

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:42.559
kind of an example I'm thinking of right now where I'm trying to guide kind of our senior

00:15:42.559 --> 00:15:48.320
data analyst and our data scientist on which tool to use. So I usually start with the end

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:52.640
user of whatever we're outputting. So, I mean, if it's a model, it's kind of a no-brainer,

00:15:52.640 --> 00:16:00.320
like Looker, the BI tool, SQL, probably not the right tool set. So for more of those problems

00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:06.559
where it's kind of automation or the model is being used as an input somewhere that may be

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:11.119
more business-facing and less of like a number where things are being calculated off, that's

00:16:11.119 --> 00:16:15.679
when I feel like that decision comes into play. So right now we have a bit of an automation project,

00:16:15.679 --> 00:16:20.400
basically at a high level, just automated reports that need to get churned out every month with a

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:25.679
heavy amount of math and calculations under the hood. So right now I'm trying to evaluate for

00:16:25.679 --> 00:16:31.440
the end users of this, what are their primary needs? Do we need this to be static, auditable,

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:38.799
and traceable? That might lend more to Python or R Markdown, right, as the tool set. Or do they

00:16:38.799 --> 00:16:43.119
need to interact with elements of this and there's less of that need for it to be a static PDF?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.559
That might put me more in the Looker camp, right? So there are aspects of it where they want to kind

00:16:48.559 --> 00:16:54.239
of see how they're doing internally for our sales team monthly, where there's just the static value

00:16:54.239 --> 00:16:58.799
could work, but they also kind of want the ability to like input new values and see how those change

00:16:58.799 --> 00:17:03.039
or how much basically something would be worth to them when they're kind of prospecting it.

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:08.560
So without going into too much detail, that kind of brings me down the path of like, wait a

00:17:08.560 --> 00:17:13.439
second, what tools are really required to meet that end user need? So I usually start with the

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:17.599
end user and then back up from there and that's kind of the same process the team goes through.

00:17:19.199 --> 00:17:25.040
I like that a lot, starting with the end user. Yeah. Jill, I see your question you said

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:31.439
was answered with that as well, but I think it brings up a point to me to think about,

00:17:32.800 --> 00:17:36.400
like you have the data analysts and data scientists as well and they're using different

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:41.280
tools, but do you sometimes have people moving from one side to the other, like data analysts

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:48.160
starting to use R and Python and then- Absolutely, yeah. So we definitely have analysts who

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:54.719
are more senior ones who are fairly strong in Python, but they're definitely stronger

00:17:54.719 --> 00:18:00.160
in the BI tools and SQL. So there are examples in the past before we had a more built-out data

00:18:00.160 --> 00:18:04.479
science team where they were doing some of that automation work and they were doing some like

00:18:04.479 --> 00:18:11.119
API calls for automated sends and marketing material, for example. But definitely

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:16.400
I try to think of like, where is their skill set strongest? And it's going to take them longer to

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:21.199
figure out how to do something in Python than it will if they just are using the tools that they

00:18:21.199 --> 00:18:25.520
use every single day. So now that we have that capability, those sorts of problems are probably

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:35.280
no longer going to them, but they can interface with that. I would say from a data munging

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:40.079
perspective, it has been super illuminating to work with like a pretty advanced analytics team

00:18:40.079 --> 00:18:46.000
to see how much they do in SQL in terms of data manipulation. It is pretty impressive.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:52.880
Being more of an R user, I honestly wouldn't think of that as my first choice for things like

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:59.359
pivoting, et cetera, but they are pretty strong in SQL. So they will often use that. That being

00:18:59.359 --> 00:19:04.079
said, there are some of them who prefer to do that sort of thing in like Python. So they'll

00:19:04.079 --> 00:19:07.359
just kind of query the database, do their data manipulation in there, and then kind of write

00:19:07.359 --> 00:19:14.800
back if they need to. Okay, thank you. I'm just scrolling through to see which other questions

