Yeah. Thanks, Katie. I saw, I think, maybe on LinkedIn at some point, that you were hiring

00:23:10.079 --> 00:23:15.119
for data science roles a few months back, and was just curious to dive deeper into,

00:23:15.119 --> 00:23:20.239
like, that topic of hiring too, and, like, what are particular things that you look for

00:23:20.239 --> 00:23:27.599
in hiring on your own team? Yeah, so from a data science perspective, I mean, the

00:23:28.479 --> 00:23:36.160
bread and butter staples are that you can program. And I do kind of primarily only focus on R or

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:42.079
Python. So while I would absolutely consider a candidate who is really strong in SAS and maybe

00:23:42.079 --> 00:23:47.119
had never used R or Python, I just feel like the talent pool, there's just, it's just already so

00:23:47.119 --> 00:23:52.400
rich in one or the other that I would not really, unless there was something else really shining

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:56.400
about that application, I would definitely favor somebody who has those skills in R or Python.

00:23:56.400 --> 00:24:01.760
In terms of which one or the other, I'm kind of agnostic, and that might be because I come from

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:06.800
being more of an R user, but I think it's just hard enough to find good people. I think trying

00:24:06.800 --> 00:24:11.199
to put that added layer of, like, you have to be strong in R or Python is way too restrictive.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:17.119
So I think the other thing, just based on where we are as a business, is the data scientist

00:24:17.119 --> 00:24:22.000
candidates I was looking for definitely needed some kind of element of not just developing the

