well, because I know, like, a lot of people have been sharing job postings and saying it's difficult

00:24:46.479 --> 00:24:51.839
hiring right now, and where, yeah, where do you generally find candidates?

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:57.280
Yeah, I mean, to be honest, it took a while, right? I mean, maybe it's the planning fallacy,

00:24:57.280 --> 00:25:03.439
but I thought it would take a while, and it took longer. In terms of where we are,

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:08.319
in terms of where we found them, so one ended up being a referral of the other,

00:25:08.319 --> 00:25:13.520
which is kind of the best situation, but I believe kind of it was just LinkedIn seeing the job

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:18.719
posting, but I absolutely got some great candidates who just ended up not being a fit for a variety

00:25:18.719 --> 00:25:24.479
of reasons through open source community forums. So I posted on Our Ladies. I posted on kind of

00:25:24.479 --> 00:25:31.680
our local Columbus tech org channel, and I definitely talked to amazing people from those

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:37.199
sources, so that's kind of always a first go-to for me is, yes, our recruiter puts it on LinkedIn,

00:25:37.199 --> 00:25:41.119
but then I take that link, and I push that out to all the open source communities that

00:25:41.119 --> 00:25:47.920
I'm involved in, so. Awesome. Thank you. Edgar, I see you had your hand raised. You want to jump in?

00:25:49.119 --> 00:25:55.520
Yeah, so I have a question. So when you're looking at candidates, and someone's looking to transition

00:25:55.520 --> 00:26:00.079
from one industry into another, how do you take that into account when they may not have the most

00:26:00.079 --> 00:26:08.640
relevant experience in the industry that they're in? Yeah, there are, I'm trying to think of, like,

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:13.920
of our whole team, there's probably only one or two people who had insurance experience.

00:26:15.280 --> 00:26:21.280
Obviously, I favor that if you had insurance experience, but again, I just find that it's

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:28.400
pretty hard to find really good people who fit your specific needs and the time you're at an

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:32.959
organization. So there are a ton of amazing data scientist candidates out there, but starting out

00:26:32.959 --> 00:26:37.520
fresh, it wasn't really the best play for me to think of somebody super junior, because there

00:26:37.520 --> 00:26:42.479
were just, there wasn't enough, like, coaching time to go around, right? So I know that can be a mixed

00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:46.319
message, because you might be thinking, like, there's tons of great candidates out there. Totally are,

00:26:46.319 --> 00:26:51.520
but I think when you're in kind of an early to mid-stage growth company, your role requirements

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:58.640
get a little more narrow, and it just can be hard to find really good people. So I,

00:26:59.920 --> 00:27:05.119
hopefully, that kind of answered your question. Is there any kind of portions I didn't address from

00:27:05.119 --> 00:27:10.400
that? I think it's, yeah, I think also kind of making yourself competitive, I think, in that

00:27:10.400 --> 00:27:16.079
terms, and you did answer that to a degree, but I think, like, I'm transitioning from education into,

00:27:16.079 --> 00:27:21.439
like, a different industry, and so, you know, how do you get past that initial, where a recruiter

00:27:21.439 --> 00:27:26.160
might say, how can I make these connections from one industry to another? And I think...

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:33.040
That's a great question. So, like I said, we definitely have hired people without insurance

00:27:33.040 --> 00:27:37.920
backgrounds, but I think what has made them really attractive is they have some sort of

00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:44.319
demonstrated ability to learn, right? And showing a passion for that, right? So I can teach you the

00:27:44.319 --> 00:27:48.640
industry. It's much harder for me to teach you, like, foundational statistics principles, to teach

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:54.479
you coding and programming. So that's always my approach, but I will say what can be a little

00:27:54.479 --> 00:28:00.239
challenging is if you ask somebody for examples of when they taught themselves a new concept, or

00:28:00.880 --> 00:28:06.800
learned a new process in the past, and they come up blank, that can be kind of a red flag for,

00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:12.160
like, hmm, like, will they pick up on the business aspect of this as quickly? I know coming out of

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:18.719
academia myself, that can be a tough transition, because you, in reality, if you've got a PhD, right,

00:28:18.719 --> 00:28:23.760
like, you have four to five years of job experience, but people don't often look at you that way

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:30.079
in the market, unfortunately, and I think that's a big miss. Unfortunately there, I think a lot of that

00:28:30.079 --> 00:28:35.439
is you just getting the opportunity to sell yourself, right? So, like, if you can just get

00:28:35.439 --> 00:28:42.880
that first interview and demonstrate how the skills you learn in your academic position

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:49.199
will translate, and, I mean, what a better example of, like, grit than completing a PhD, right? Like, if you

00:28:49.199 --> 00:28:55.040
can sell yourself on the transition of your skills, I think you can succeed in that interview process,

00:28:55.040 --> 00:28:59.520
but I think where people probably, unfortunately, get overlooked is just getting that first interview.

00:29:00.560 --> 00:29:05.280
So I think a lot of that, if you're coming straight from academia, is, like, tailoring your interest to

00:29:05.280 --> 00:29:10.239
the right companies. So this is just a generalization. I wouldn't say this is true of every major

00:29:10.239 --> 00:29:15.839
company. Absolutely not. I've definitely seen large companies that have a appreciation for academic

00:29:15.839 --> 00:29:21.680
talent, but in general, I think startups or mid, like, mid-stage growth companies tend to be a little

00:29:21.680 --> 00:29:26.800
bit more friendly to the academic crowd, because there are folks there. I think if you can find a

00:29:26.800 --> 00:29:32.640
manager that you might be working under who has their PhD, they are going to be more alert to you

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:38.800
as a high talent potential. So our recruiters, for example, they are the first stop, but I am

00:29:38.800 --> 00:29:43.439
looking in there all the time at people coming in, and I will tell them, hey, just because this is a

00:29:43.439 --> 00:29:47.280
senior role, don't roll somebody out just because they have a PhD and no work experience. I want to

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:52.319
see them, but if you don't have the hiring manager doing that, then you might get overlooked, and you

00:29:52.319 --> 00:30:02.239
might not even get that first conversation. Thank you. Yeah, Katie, and actually, like, elaborating on

00:30:02.239 --> 00:30:08.719
that a little bit, I can see that Tatiana asked a great question. If you want to jump in, Tatiana,

00:30:08.719 --> 00:30:16.160
about how Katie went from one area to another, moving into analytics. Yeah, that was very

00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:21.839
interesting, and I recently interviewed for, or actually, I was interviewed for how I shifted my

00:30:21.839 --> 00:30:26.880
careers, and one of the aspects that I highlighted was self-promotion, especially we as, I don't want

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:32.479
to, like, generalize or miss everybody out, but as women, we tend to undersell ourselves, I feel like,

00:30:32.479 --> 00:30:39.119
and it's very important not to, like, get all that mental self-talk out of the picture and just go

00:30:39.119 --> 00:30:42.800
ahead and sell yourself, because if you don't, if you don't speak up, and if you don't know how to

00:30:42.800 --> 00:30:47.199
promote your persona, how to think through the eyes of the person who is hiring you, meaning so

00:30:47.199 --> 00:30:51.920
you can showcase how your analytical thinking that you developed during your PhD or your master's,

00:30:51.920 --> 00:30:56.319
or whatever, how it translates into your business case is very important, and then you can do

00:30:56.319 --> 00:31:01.839
projects on the side that actually show that here is an example of how I did it, because nobody

00:31:01.839 --> 00:31:05.760
prevents you from doing courses on the side and do projects on the side, but this is my penchant,

00:31:05.760 --> 00:31:09.839
and the question was if you could speak more about your personal experience, how you transitioned

00:31:09.839 --> 00:31:18.000
from psychology to analytics and data science. Yeah, so I was in a PhD program, and they can vary,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:23.760
but mine started in clinical psych, so there's a heavy focus on research, so Ohio State's a pretty

00:31:23.760 --> 00:31:29.599
big research institution, so what was clinical psych, and so technically a part of it is getting

00:31:29.599 --> 00:31:34.800
your license as a clinician and seeing clients, that was not the intent of my program, so like,

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:39.439
my professor hired me because he, he chose me because he wanted me to work on academic research

00:31:39.439 --> 00:31:44.959
with him, so that was a heavy amount in training of statistics, statistics courses, experimental

00:31:44.959 --> 00:31:51.839
methods, and then programming as well, so that alone though, especially in today's market, would have

00:31:51.839 --> 00:31:58.640
been a bit hard to sell as a transition, and I feel like what you need to like, focus on is that

00:31:58.640 --> 00:32:03.520
one, that first opportunity that's transitional, that's the bridge, I think you can get it from

00:32:03.520 --> 00:32:09.760
user groups, and that's another huge value of the open source community. For me, it was a kind of

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:14.400
graduate assistant social associateship with Nationwide Insurance, so they basically bought,

00:32:15.119 --> 00:32:18.959
you know, kind of fledgling PhDs out of their teaching contract, which they didn't want to do

00:32:18.959 --> 00:32:24.000
anyways, and they, you know, would pay them to work in their analytics department, so it was a great gig

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:28.880
for me, and it was that like first exposure, and then once I had that, like my network opened up, I

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:34.239
had quote-unquote industry experience, even though it was white, and the path was just open from there

00:32:34.239 --> 00:32:41.280
for me to fly on. I think with masters of analytics and data science programs today, it's like a little,

00:32:41.280 --> 00:32:46.800
I think some of these core PhD and master's programs can get overlooked, and I think the

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:52.560
way to sell yourself is to, one, just learn to sell yourself, which is a very foreign concept in academia,

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:59.280
but two, also to get that first experience, and I think if it's hard to find, user groups are a

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:03.520
great way to start. Open source communities are an exceptional way to start, because you will,

00:33:04.079 --> 00:33:09.839
at the very least, dialogue and meet people who can expose you to that first industry opportunity

00:33:09.920 --> 00:33:17.280
that's more formal than the, like just user group itself. I will also say there's a few programs,

00:33:17.280 --> 00:33:23.359
so I'll throw one in the chat, that I am like volunteer at, so one is called the Erdos Institute,

00:33:23.359 --> 00:33:29.439
and it's founded by math PhDs, and their whole purpose is to train PhDs who have decided academia

00:33:29.439 --> 00:33:34.479
is not for them to get that industry experience, so it's kind of like a boot camp, but the talent is

00:33:34.479 --> 00:33:40.239
just incredible there, and also the training and prep for industry, so that's kind of another like

00:33:40.239 --> 00:33:45.040
segue example, but like you kind of just need to find that first connection, I think, and that's the

00:33:45.040 --> 00:33:52.400
hardest, hardest part. That would be great if you could share those links after, Katie. Yeah, I can

00:33:52.400 --> 00:33:59.439
share them on LinkedIn too, but kind of following up on this topic too, there was an anonymous

00:33:59.439 --> 00:34:05.439
question sent to me that was, what are the skills that you look for in an entry level

00:34:05.439 --> 00:34:12.320
data scientist from someone who has a degree in operations research and financial engineering,

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:19.040
but is having a difficult time landing a job, and would love to just hear more about like what tips

00:34:19.040 --> 00:34:26.239
you have for selling like yourself and getting that role too. Yeah, so entry level, I'd say

00:34:26.879 --> 00:34:33.280
the things that I would look for is, I guess it's all basic, and I'm probably talking, or all

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:37.919
relative, and I'm talking to some probably fairly advanced R users, but at least like that basic

00:34:37.919 --> 00:34:43.600
foundational skill set, so we have a take-home project as part of our interview process. Also, I

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:47.360
think in just asking questions as an interview, you can tell how deep their skill set goes,

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:52.159
but from a basic level, I would hope they could do the bulk of the analyses in either R or Python,

00:34:52.159 --> 00:34:57.280
but it might not be as well set up as somebody who I might interview for like more of a

00:34:57.280 --> 00:35:02.239
intermediate or senior role, so instead of, you know, using functions and not repeating yourself,

00:35:02.239 --> 00:35:07.520
it might just be getting the job done, and if the role is really entry level, that might be okay,

00:35:07.520 --> 00:35:13.919
right, like that might just show that they have the potential to grow, so I'd say that's one,

00:35:13.919 --> 00:35:18.239
it's like kind of just assessing where their code is at, and just knowing that they can code,

00:35:18.239 --> 00:35:23.520
but it probably needs some work, right, like they have room to grow. I'd say probably more

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:28.959
important to me is their ability to like prioritize and take things into their own

00:35:28.959 --> 00:35:34.879
hands and take on work independently with some guidance, right, so some demonstrated experience

00:35:34.879 --> 00:35:39.840
of having done that in the past is super important, I think for any level, honestly,

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:45.040
to give you the comfort that you know they can grow into more of that intermediate senior position.

